"EIS 14Written evidence submitted by the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Anti-Corruption&#xa0;Executive Summary and Recommendations&#xa0;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe EITI has the potential to positively impact the UK extractive industries; we recommend that the Government gives due consideration to how its principles can be tailored to the specific domestic context and in doing so demonstrate the importance of national-level ownership and adaption.\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe impact of EITI implementation will depend on adherence to optional elements.  We recommend the Government provides data in an accessible format with sufficient contextual information. Contracts regulating extraction should also be published. \n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government should consider embedding EITI obligations into existing governance structures where possible, rather than creating additional layers of reporting.\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe extractive industries pose a significant reputational risk to the UK as a centre for global business.  Particular concerns are raised by the use of nominee directors and opaque corporate structures.  Regulation of both the London Stock Exchange and the Alternative Investment Market has proven insufficient and should be strengthened. \n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nBy creating a public register of beneficial ownership the Government will develop a more transparent business environment and help prevent the laundering of illegitimately raised natural resource assets, often from conflict or weak governance states.  \n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Government should ensure enforcement mechanisms have sufficient resources and expertise to realise our strong anti-bribery legislation. \nBackground&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;Introduction&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nMaking the EITI work in a UK context&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nImpact of the UK implementing EITI&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nLimiting the administrative burden &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nReputational risk to the UK &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nMaking the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n February 2013, \nAustralia’s Pilot Progress Report\n [pdf].  Available \nhere\n. \n House of Commons Library, September 2013, \nShale gas and fracking\n [pdf].  Available \nhere\n. \n David Cameron, May 2013, \nLetter to Crown Dependency Leaders\n.  Available \nhere\n. \n EITI International Secretariat, July 2013, \nThe EITI Standard\n [pdf].  Available \nhere\n. \n EITI International Secretariat, July 2013, \nThe EITI Standard\n [pdf].  Available \nhere\n. \n London Mining Network, February 2012, \nUK-Listed Mining Companies &amp; The Case for Stricter Oversight \n[pdf].\n \nAvailable \nhere\n.  \n Espenlaub, S., Khurshed, A., Mohamed, A., 2008, \nIPO survival in a reputational market \n[pdf]. Available \nhere\n. \n BBC News, 2007, \nAIM stock market ‘like a casino’. \nAvailable \nhere\n. \n Rights and Accountability in Development, March 2013, \nAsset laundering and AIM; Congo, Corporate Misconduct and the Market Value of Human Rights\n, Oxford\n ibid\n Asset International’s Chief Investment Officer, August 2013, \nInvestors Demand Clampdown on Corruption. \nAvailable \nhere\n. \n EITI, March 2013, \nDriving transparency in extractive industries to minimize risks for investors. \nAvailable \nhere\n. \n EITI International Secretariat, July 2013, \nThe EITI Standard\n [pdf].  Available \nhere\n.\n Rights and Accountability in Development, March 2013, \nAsset laundering and AIM; Congo, Corporate Misconduct and the Market Value of Human Rights\n, Oxford\n \nibid\n"